name: adipose tissue
explanation: Adipose tissue is loose connective tissue that consists of adipocytes. It stores energy in the form of fats, and insulated the body.

name: anatomy
explanation: The branch of biology concerned with the study of the structure of organisms and their parts

name: basement membrane
explanation: The thin layer (made primarily of protein fibres) that separate the epithelium from the tissue underneath.

name: blood
explanation: A type of connective tissue. Fluid used to transport nutrients, waste, oxygen, and carbon dioxide through the body. It is composed primarily plasma (a fluid matrix), red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.

name: bone
explanation: Substance that forms the skeleton of the body, composed mostly of calcium phosphate and calcium carbonate. Bones support and protect internal organs, and muscles pull against bones to make the body move. The bone marrow in the middle of the bone makes and stores blood cells.

name: cardiac muscle
explanation: Cardiac muscle is an involuntary, striated muscle that is found in the walls and histological foundation of the heart

name: cartilage

vettings.explanation: Cartilage is a connective tissue that is softer and more flexible than bone. It is found in many places in the body such as between joints.
vettings.author: martyn

explanation: Soft muscle tissue, connecting joints and bones.

name: collagen
explanation: Collagen is the main structural protein in the extracellular space in the various connective tissues in animal bodies.  As the main component of connective tissue, it is the most abundant protein in mammals.

name: collagenous fiber
explanation: any one of the tough, white protein fibers that constitute much of the intercellular substance and the connective tissue of the body. Collagenous fibers contain collagen

name: connective tissue
explanation: Tissue which connects, binds and supports other tissue. It maintains the form of its body and its organs. Some is specialized, there are several types like bone and cartilage.

name: connective tissue fiber

vettings.explanation:
There are three types of fibers in the intercellular matrix of connective tissue:
1) collagen fibers
2) reticular fibers
3) elastic fibers
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: Component of intercellular matrix, helps with binding tissues together, support, and other functions of connective tissue

name: control center
explanation: The control center is the part of homeostatic regulation that receives and processes information from the receptor.

name: dense irregular connective tissue
explanation: Dense irregular connective tissue contains non elastic collagenous fibers in a dense, disorderly arrangement. Because of its strength, it is found in the dermis, walls of large organs, glandular tissue and organ capsules.

name: dense regular connective tissue
explanation: Dense regular connective tissue connects tissues within the body. An example of dense regular connective tissue is tendons which connects muscles to bone.

name: effector
explanation: An effector is part of the negative feedback loop in our body that helps to maintain homeostasis. For example, in controlling the temperature, the hypothalamus in the brain acts as a "thermostat" or control centre, and the effector for that loop would be our sweat glands and blood vessels.

name: elastic fiber
explanation: Elastic fibers are bundles of proteins that are found in connective tissue. They are produced in the arteries by fibroblasts and smooth muscle cells. They are like elastic bands, and can stretch to ~1.5 times their length, but go back to normal when relaxed. Examples include elastin, elaunin, and oxytalan.

name: elastin
explanation: A highly elastic protein in connective tissue and allows many tissues in the body to resume their shape after stretching or contracting.

name: endocrine gland
explanation: A gland, part of the endocrine system, that produces a hormone. Examples: pituitary gland, pancreas, thyroid gland.

name: endocrine system
explanation: An organ system whose primary role is to produce hormones. They are then secreted into the circulatory system, regulating a variety of body functions like reproduction, sleep, and metabolism. The primary glands include the pineal gland, pituitary gland, pancreas, ovaries, testes, and thyroid gland.

name: epithelial tissue
explanation: Epithelial tissue covers the outside of the body, lines organs and cavities within the body, and forms glands. The cells are tightly packed and are either shaped cuboidal, columnar, or squamous. There are also different numbers of layers: simple, stratified, or pseudostratified.

name: exocrine gland

vettings.explanation: They are connected to the surface. Protects the rest of epithelium through secretion.
vettings.author: jacob

explanation: Exocrine glands are glands that secrete their products into ducts

name: feedback loop
explanation: There is a positive, and negative type. They help to maintain homeostasis in an organism.

name: fibroblast
explanation: A fibroblast is a type of cell that synthesizes the extracellular matrix and collagen, the structural framework (stroma) for animal tissues, and plays a critical role in wound healing.  Fibroblasts are the most common cells of connective tissue in animals.

name: fibrous connective tissue
explanation: This specific connective tissue is high-strength, slightly stretchy tissue consists mainly of collagen, a protein which is known for providing strength and stability.

name: functional anatomy
explanation: When an organism's anatomy serves a specific functional purpose, such as the ears of Hares, or the size and shape of various organisms who adapt for similar environmental challenges.

name: glandular epithelium

vettings.explanation: The cells of the glandular epithelium are generally columnar or cuboidal.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation:
Epithelium tissue which produces glands, organs which secrete products. Examples include sebacious gland.
Sac structures

name: glia
explanation: Glia cells are non-neuronal cells that maintain homeostasis, form myelin, and provide support and protection for neurons in the central and peripheral nervous systems.

name: homeostasis

vettings.explanation: The term "homeostasis" combines "homeo" ("similar") and "stasis" ("standing still"), yielding the idea of "staying the same."
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: Homeostasis is the maintenance of a steady sate, or internal balance regardless of the external environment. It typically involves negative feedback loops to counteract changes. For example, when you exercise, body temperature increases, causing sweat which cools the body down.

name: homeostatic control system
explanation: Homeostasis regulates the body's internal environment to maintain a stable environment. Homeostatic control systems contain a sensor or receptor that detects changes in internal or external environment, a control center that receives information form the  sensor to decide on a response, and an effector which receives information from the control center to bring around change.

name: ligament

vettings.explanation: Connects bones to bones
vettings.author: andy

vettings.explanation: The ligament is a fibrous connective tissue that connects bones together.
vettings.author: martyn

vettings.explanation: Ligaments are tough fibrous bands of connective tissue which serve to support internal organs and hold bones together in proper articulation at the joints.
vettings.author: jacob

comments.explanation: Please be more thorough with your definitions and explanations, as well as with your vetting.... This concept requires more work.
comments.author: maria

explanation: Connective tissue

name: loose connective tissue
explanation: Loose connective tissue is a kind of connective tissue that is found in vertebrates. It helps to hold organs in place, attaches epithelial and other tissues together, and surrounds the blood vessels and nerves. For example, telae connects mucous and serous membranes to the muscular layer.

name: macrophage
explanation: A large cell able to digest harmful foreign particles, bacteria, and dead or dying cells. Either found stationary in the tissues or as a mobile white blood cell, especially at sites of infection.

name: muscle tissue

vettings.explanation: Muscular tissues contract in response to nerve signals; the cells are called muscle fibres.
vettings.author: ashley

explanation: the tissue that makes up muscles and allow the muscle to contract/relax. Muscle tissue can be smooth, skeletal or cardiac.

name: negative feedback
explanation: A system which uses a sensor, control, and effector in order to prevent or minimize deviations from a set point. An example is homeostasis, or more specifically, temperature regulation.

name: nervous system
explanation: Transmits information between locations very quickly, and nerve impulses can be received by neurons, muscle cells, and endocrine cells. The information conveyed depends on a signal's pathway, not the type of signal.

name: nervous tissue
explanation:
The main tissue component of the two parts of the nervous system; the brain and spinal cord of the central nervous system (CNS), and the branching peripheral nerves of the peripheral nervous system (PNS)
Regulates and controls bodily functions and activity

name: neurons
explanation: The neuron is the basic working unit of the brain, a specialized cell designed to transmit information to other nerve cells, muscle, or gland cells. Neurons are cells within the nervous system that transmit information to other nerve cells, muscle, or gland cells.

name: organ
explanation: An organ is a collection of tissues joined in a structural unit to serve a common function.

name: organ system
explanation: an organ system is a group of organs that work together to perform one or more functions.

name: physiology
explanation: The study of the biological functions of living organisms.

name: positive feedback
explanation: A type of feedback loop which the result reinforces the stimulus.

name: pseudostratified columnar
explanation: A pseudostratified epithelium is a type of epithelium that, though comprising only a single layer of cells, has its cell nuclei positioned in a manner suggestive of stratified epithelia.

name: receptor
explanation: A receptor detects changes in the internal or external environment, and sends information to the hypothalamus. For example, baroreceptors are located in the walls of arteries and can detect an increase in blood pressure. The receptors then send a signal to the hypothalamus, which sends a message to the heart.

name: reticular fiber
explanation: Reticular fiber is a type of fiber in connective tissue composed of type III collagen secreted by reticular cells.

name: simple columnar

vettings.explanation: E.g. intestines, absorbs nutrients in small lines
vettings.author: jacob

explanation: Simple columnar is a type of epithelial tissue which resembles pillars.

name: simple cuboidal
explanation: This is a kind of epithelium that is made of a single layer of cube-like cells that have large, sphere shaped nuclei. They are found on the surface of the ovaries, and on the lining of nephrons, where the cells perform secretion and absorption.

name: simple squamous

vettings.explanation: Simple squamous epithelium is often permeable and occurs where small molecules pass quickly through membranes via filtration or diffusion.  Simple squamous epithelia are found in capillaries, alveoli, glomeruli, and other tissues where rapid diffusion is required.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: A single layer of flat cells in contact with the basal lamina of the epithelium.

name: smooth muscle
explanation: is a type of muscle tissue that surrounds organs (and blood vessels). They are responsible for involuntary movement and are triggered by impulses from the nervous system. Smooth muscle contractions can cause involuntary expansion (urinary bladder wall, uterus wall), motion (intestines) or change the shape of the organ (lens of eye).

name: specialized cell
explanation: A cell that is meant to perform a specific function and has the necessary adaptations to do so efficiently. Examples include skin cells, neurons, and blood cells.

name: stratified cuboidal
explanation: Type of epithelial tissue composed of multiple layers of cube-shaped cells, can be found in the pancreas, salivary glands, and sweat glands (areas exposed to greater potential for damage). Functions include sweat secretion and aiding in sperm production and secretion of ovarian hormones.

name: stratified squamous
explanation:
Consists of flattened epithelial cells arranged in layers upon a cutaneous membrane
This type of epithelium is well suited to areas in the body subject to constant abrasion, as it is the thickest and layers can be sequentially sloughed off and replaced before the basement membrane is exposed
Forms the outermost layer of the skin and the inner lining of the mouth and esophagus

name: striated (skeletal) muscle
explanation: It is a type of muscular tissue, and is responsible for our body's voluntary movements.

name: tendon
explanation: A tendon is a tough band of fibrous connective tissue that usually connects muscle to bone and is capable of withstanding tension.  Tendons are similar to ligaments; both are made of collagen.  Ligaments join one bone to another bone, while tendons connect muscle to bone.

name: tissue
explanation: tissue is a cellular organizational level intermediate between cells and a complete organ.

name: acclimatization

vettings.explanation: How birds and mammals change the amount of insulation depending on seasonal temperature to adjust to the climate - one example is an animal growing more fur in the winter.
vettings.author: hannah

comments.explanation: Remember that acclimatization is not restricted to body temperature. Other physiological parameters also go through this process: number of red blood cells in response to higher altitude, changes in vision in response to lower light, etc.
comments.author: maria

explanation: The response of an organism to the change in temperature in their environment.

name: adaptation
explanation: a trait in an organism which has been evolved and maintained by natural selction, presumably benefical to organism due to environment

name: basal metabolic rate (BMR)
explanation: The metabolic rate of an endotherm at rest at a comfortable temperature.

name: behavioural response
explanation: Behavioural changes to control body temperature. Ex. Some invertebrates use posture to minimize or maximize absorption of solar heat.

name: bioenergetic strategy
explanation: The bioenergetic strategy is the strategy that living organisms employ to regulate inner body temperatures and energy.

name: bioenergetics

vettings.explanation: Overall flow and transformation of energy in an animal, determines how much food an animal needs, and relates to its size, activity and environment.
vettings.author: jacob

explanation: Bioenergetics is the study of the transfer of energy between living organisms.

name: circulatory adaptation
explanation: Circulatory adaptation refers to the regulation of the amount of blood flowing between the body core and the skin. In vasodilation, blood flow in the skin increases and facilitates heat loss. In vasoconstriction, blood flow in the skin decreases, which lowers heat loss.

name: conformer
explanation: An organism that has no need to control their internal environment since the external environment is fairly constant in terms of temperature, oxygen content, and nutrients.

name: counter-current heat exchange
explanation: A circulatory adaptation that is the transfer of heat between fluids that flows in opposite directions. Marine organisms and endothermic insects use this method to regulate their internal temperature. (E.g. bottlenose dolphin)

name: ectotherm

vettings.explanation: The term "cold blooded" is not technically correct, as the blood temperature of an ectotherm varies with the ambient environmental temperature (e.g. a reptile regulating its temperature by basking in the sun would not have "cold" blood).
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: A "cold-blooded" animal, or any organism that depends on external heat sources to control their internal temperature and do not internally generate heat.

name: endotherm
explanation: Generate heat by metabolism, independent of the environment. Endotherms can be active and survive at a great variation of external tempratures, but require a high energy quantity to produce heat continuously.

name: estivation

vettings.explanation: Also called summer torpor (because it allows animals to survive in extreme heat/water scarcity)
vettings.author: hannah

explanation:
State of animal dormancy, similar to hibernation, characterized by inactivity and a lowered metabolic rate
Entered in response to high temperatures and arid conditions

name: evaporative loss

vettings.explanation: Evaporation is the removal of heat from the surface of a liquid that is losing some of its molecules as gas; evaporative loss is a type of adaptation that animals used to regulate their internal temperature, and involves losing heat through the evaporation of water in sweat.
vettings.author: ashley

explanation: Loss of body of water by evaporation of water from the body to the air; a heat control mechanism and a factor in water balance studies.

name: fever
explanation: Fever, also known as pyrexia and febrile response, is defined as having a temperature above the normal range due to an increase in the body's temperature set point.  The increase in set-point triggers increased muscle contraction and causes a feeling of cold.  This results in greater heat production and efforts to conserve heat.  When the set-point temperature returns to normal, a person feels hot, becomes flushed, and may begin to sweat.  Fevers do not typically go higher than 41 to 42*C (105.8 to 107.6*F).

name: homeotherm
explanation: An organism which maintains constant body temperature. An example being a river otter.

name: hyperthermia

vettings.explanation: Hyperthermia is elevated body temperature due to failed thermoregulation.  Hyperthermia differs from fever in that the body's temperature set point remains unchanged.  The most common cause of hyperthermia is heat stroke, which occurs when thermoregulation is overwhelmed by a combination of excessive metabolic production of heat (exertion), excessive environmental heat, and insufficient or impaired heat loss.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: above normal body temperature

name: hypothalamus

vettings.explanation:
Also responsible for the production of many essential hormones. Primary function is homeostasis. 

http://www.healthline.com/human-body-maps/hypothalamus?scrlybrkr
vettings.author: hannah

explanation: Hypothalamus is a region of the brain with many functions, one of which is to control thermoregulation

name: hypothermia
explanation: Hypothermia is when the body's core temperature drops below the normal range. In humans, the average temperature is 37 - 37.8 degrees Celsius, and hypothermia is defined as 35 degrees or lower.

name: insulation
explanation: Insulation is a material or substance used to prevent heat from escaping. Examples include feathers, fur, and blubber.

name: kleptothermy
explanation: Kleptothermy is a type of thermoregulation in which an organism shares the heat of another organism (e.g. huddling). This can occur with both endotherms and ectotherms.

name: metabolic heat production
explanation: This refers to the reactions in the body that cause heat loss or production . For example, heat production is increased by muscle activity, like moving or shivering.

name: metabolic rate
explanation: the amount of energy expended while at rest in a neutrally temperate environment, while the digestive system is inactive, which requires about twelve hours of fasting

name: normal body temperature
explanation: The set point of an organisms thermoregulation. Human's have a normal body temperature between 36 and 38 degrees Celsius.

name: poikilotherm
explanation: An organism with no mechanisms for homeostasis, instead, its body temperature fluctuates greatly with the external temperature.

name: regulator

vettings.explanation: Does not have to pertain to temperature; any organism with internal control mechanisms to moderate internal change in the face of external, environmental fluctuation is a regulator.
vettings.author: amanda

explanation: An organism that can mantain a constant internal body temperature through homeostasis independent of the external environment. These kind of animals are endothermic birds and mammals, along with ectothermic tropical reptiles and some organisms deep in the ocean or in deep lakes.

name: standard metabolic rate (SMR)

vettings.explanation: Only for ectothermic organism: the metabolic rate of an ectotherm at rest at a specific temperature
vettings.author: hannah

explanation: The minimum metabolic rate needed to sustain life at a specified temperature

name: thermoregulation

vettings.explanation: Process by which animals maintain an internal temperature within a normal range.
vettings.author: jacob

explanation: Thermoregulation is a process that allows your body to maintain its core internal temperature (for homeostasis).

name: torpor
explanation: Torpor is a state of decreased physiological activity in an animal, usually by reduced body temperature and metabolic rate.  Torpor enables animals to survive periods of reduced food availability.  The term "torpor" can refer to the time a hibernator spends at low body temperature, lasting days to weeks, or it can refer to a period of low body temperature and metabolism lasting less than 24 hours ("daily torpor").

name: vasodilation
explanation: Vasodilation is a circulatory adaptation where the blood flow in the skin increases as blood vessels dilate which facilitates heat loss.

name: active immunity
explanation: immunity from producing antibodies as a response to antigen

name: adaptive immune system

vettings.explanation: The adaptive immune system creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to subsequent encounters with that pathogen.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: The adaptive immune system is a subsystem of the immune system that uses specialized cells to eliminate pathogens

name: agglutination
explanation: Agglutination is a process used by the immune system to inactivate invading foreign substances. Antibodies, proteins made by the immune system, bind to antigens/foreign bodies forming an antigen-antibody complex. Agglutination is a clump of antigen-antibody complexes, which helps phagocytes ingest these substances and inactivate them.

name: AIDS
explanation: AIDS is a syndrome caused by the HIV virus when the infected person's immune system is too weak to fight off most infections. This is the last stage of HIV infection where the infected person's body is no longer able to defend itself.

name: anaphylactic shock

vettings.explanation: Analphylactic shock is a serious allergic reaction with rapid onset and may cause death.  The primary treatment of anaphylaxis is epinephrine injection into a muscle, intravenous fluids, and positioning the person flat.  Anaphylaxis can occur in response to almost any foreign substance (e.g. venom from insect bites or stings, foods, and medication).
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: Anaphylactic shock is an extreme reaction (the immune system releases chemicals into the body) to an antigen that the body is hypersensitive to. When the body is in this state, blood pressure drops suddenly and airways narrow, blocking normal breathing.

name: antibody
explanation: A large, Y-shaped protein produced mainly by plasma cells that is used by the immune system to neutralize pathogens such as bacteria and viruses.

name: antigen
explanation: Simply, and antigen is an unwanted toxin. The introduction of an antigen with induce an immune response from the body, as antibodies are distributed to combat the foreign substance. Examples of an antigen: a bacteria, foreign blood cells, a rejected transplanted organ.

name: antigen disposal mechanism
explanation: The ways the body rids itself of foreign substances, an immune system response.

name: antigen fragment
explanation: Also known as the epitope, a specific piece of the antigen that is recognized by the immune system to which the antibody binds to.

name: antigen neutralization

vettings.explanation: The antibody blocks the site on the virus that the virus would normally use to invade its target cell
vettings.author: hannah

explanation:
Sometimes called neutralizing antigen.
An antibody that defends a cell from an antigen or infectious body by neutralizing any effect it has biologically

name: antigen precipitation
explanation:
A specific chemical interaction between antibodies produced by B cells of the white blood cells and antigens during immune reaction.

A soluble antibody reacts with a soluble antigen to give an insoluble product or the precipitate. Soluble antibodies that aggregate soluble antigens are called precipitins. Soluble antigen that induces the formation of a specific precipitin is called a precipitinogen.

name: antigen presenting cell
explanation: An antigen-presenting cell (APC) is a cell that displays antigen complexed with major histocompatibility complexes (MHCs) on their surfaces.  This process is known as antigen presentation.  Almost all types of cells can serve as some form of APC.  They are found in a variety of tissue types.

name: antigen-antibody complex
explanation: The antigen-antibody complex is a molecule formed when an antibody binds to a soluble antigen. Once the antigen and antibody are bound together they act as an antigen with a specific epitope. (An epitope is the point where an antibody attaches to an antigen)

name: antimicrobial protein
explanation: Antimicrobial peptides (AMPs), also called host defense peptides (HDPs) are part of the innate immune response found among all classes of life.

name: artificial immunity
explanation: artificial immunity involves introducing an antibody into the system once a person has already been infected with a disease, ultimately relieving the present symptoms of the sickness and preventing re-occurrence.

name: autoimmune disease

vettings.explanation: Depending on the type, an autoimmune disease can affect one or many different types of body tissue. It can also cause abnormal organ growth and changes in organ function.
vettings.author: sharon

explanation: Autoimmune diseases are when problems with the immune system cause it to mistake healthy cells as invaders and repeatedly attack them.

name: B cell
explanation: B cells are a type of lymphocyte which is a type of white blood cell. B cells mature into plasma cells which produce antibodies while other B cells evolve into memory B cells.

name: CD4 protein
explanation: CD4 is a glycoprotein that is found on the surface of immune cells like T helper cells and monocytes.  It is a very important part of the immune system, as CD4+ T helper cells help send signals to other immune cells to help destroy infectious particles.

name: CD8 protein
explanation: A transmembrane glycoprotein that serves as a co-receptor for the T cell receptor.

name: cell-mediated response
explanation:
An immune response that responds to any cell that recognizes when an MHC marker is abnormal (e.g. tumor cell, pathogen). Typically T cells are used to respond to the aberrant MHC markers.  

1. T cell receptor recognizes and binds to the foreign antigen.
2. Interleukins (from helper t cells) stimulate T cell activation
3a. MHC I (+endogenous antigen): T cells proliferate, producing cytotoxic T cells (destroy cell displaying antigen)
3b. MHC II (+exogenous antigen): Helper t cells release interleukins, stimulating B cells (and NK lymphocytes) to produce antibodies that destroy antigen

name: chemokine
explanation: A type of signalling protein (or cytokines) which attract white blood cells to where they're needed.

name: class I MHC molecule
explanation: One of the two major types of MHC molecules, span the membrane of almost every cell in an organism whereas class II molecules are limited to the cells of the immune system (macrophages, lymphocytes). Allows T-Lymphocytes to detect cells like macrophages that have ingested infection microorganisms and bind to the digested foreign fragments attached to the MHC molecule.

name: class II MHC molecule
explanation: A class of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules normally found only on antigen-presenting cells such as phagocytes and B cells. These cells are important in initiating immune responses.

name: complement fixation
explanation: It is a part of the immune system that enhances (complements) the ability of antibodies and phagocytic cells to clear microbes and damaged cells from an organism, promotes inflammation, and attacks the pathogen's plasma membrane. It is part of the innate immune system which is not adaptable and does not change over the course of an individual's lifetime. It can be recruited and brought into action by the adaptive immune system.

name: complement protein
explanation: Complement proteins are plasma proteins that react with one another to make a foreign cell more susceptible to phagocytosis.  They induce a series of inflammatory responses that help fight infection.  Complement proteins are part of the innate immune system.

name: cytotoxic T cell
explanation: A cytotoxic T cell is a type of T cell activated by cytokines, which can bind to and kill cells which should be removed, such as infected cells or cancer cells.

name: eosinophil

vettings.explanation: Eosinophils are a variety of white blood cells and one of the immune system components responsible for combating multicellular parasites and certain infections in vertebrates.  Along with mast cells and basophils, eosinophils also control mechanisms associated with allergy and asthma.  Eosinophils are acid-loving cells.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: a white blood cell containing granules that are readily stained by eosin. Types of antibodies

name: epitope
explanation: the part of an antigen molecule to which an antibody attaches itself

name: free antigen
explanation: An antigen that is not bound to anything.

name: helper T cell
explanation: Helper T cells help activate cytotoxic T cells and macrophages to attack infected cells, or stimulate B cells to produce antibodies.

name: humoral response
explanation: The humoral immune response is the aspect of immunity that is mediated my  molecules that are found in fluids outside the cell, like antibodies. "Humoral" refers to the the fact that the substances involved are found in humors, or body fluids.

name: immunodeficiency disease

vettings.explanation:
For further thought, is autoimmune disease the same as AIDS? (AID vs. AIDS)
Answer: It's not.
http://www.pemphigus.org/explaining-your-autoimmune-disease-aid-is-not-aids/

This just kinda blew my mind.
vettings.author: sharon

explanation: A condition the inhibits the body's ability to defends itself against infection/disease - i.e. a malfunctioning immune system that leads to severer, longer lasting and more frequent infections. An immunodeficiency can be primary (present from birth, usually hereditary) or secondary (develop later in life, often from use of drugs to treat another disorder).

name: immunoglobulin
explanation: Antibodies. Proteins produced by the immune system as a response to antigens. They can then recognize and bind to the antigen, identifying the antigens to the immune system.

name: infected cell (non-APC)

vettings.explanation: Non APC cells express MHC class I molecules
vettings.author: nuala

vettings.explanation: Non-APC = Non-antigen-presenting cell
vettings.author: andy

explanation: L

name: inflammatory response

vettings.explanation: The swelling is caused by a release of histamine (or other chemicals) that make blood vessels leak fluid into the tissue
vettings.author: hannah

vettings.explanation: The function of inflammation is to eliminate the initial cause of cell injury, clear out necrotic cells and tissues damaged from the original injury and the inflammatory process, and to initiate tissue repair.  The classical signs of inflammation are heat, pain, redness, swelling, and loss of function.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: Occurs when tissues are injured by bacteria, trauma, toxins, heat, or any other cause.

name: innate immune system
explanation: The part of the immune system which reacts to pathogens in toxics in a generic way, with a general, pre-determined response.

name: interferon
explanation: Interferons are a group of signalling proteins made and released by host cells in response to the presence of several pathogens, such as viruses, bacteria, parasites, and tumour cells.  In a typical scenario, a virus-infecting cell will release interferons causing nearby cells to heighten their anti-viral defences.

name: lupus
explanation: Lupus is an autoimmune disorder which causes chronic inflammation throughout various parts of the body. There are three different types, discoid, drug induced and systemic.

name: lymphocyte

vettings.explanation: There are two type: B-cells and T-cells. B cells produce antibodies, while T-cells destroy infected cells.
vettings.author: amanda

explanation: a form of small leukocyte (white blood cell) with a single round nucleus, occurring especially in the lymphatic system.

name: lysozyme
explanation: A lysozyme is an enzyme that is destructive of bacteria and acts as an antiseptic

name: macrophage
explanation: Cells formed in response to an infection or accumulation of damaged or dead cells. Macrophages recognize, engulf and destroy target cells. It then presents the microbe's antigen on its surface to alert other white blood cells to the presence of an invading particle. This allows blood cells to multiply and stimulate an immune response against it.

name: mast cell
explanation: A mast cell is a type of white blood cell that releases mediators such as histamine into the environment which are responsible for allergy symptoms such as inflammation and increased mucus production.

name: memory B cell
explanation: Memory B cells that are formed after a primary infection and help to generate a faster, stronger immune response to avoid re-infection.

name: MHC glycoprotein
explanation:
A Major Histocompatibility Complex, that includes both MHC class I glycoproteins and MHC class II glycoproteins. An MHC molecule can bind to the proteins of antigens, and then present itself at the surface of a T cell, eliciting an immune response (T cells only recognize antigens as complexes with the MHC molecule). 

The difference between class I and II is how they each is specialized to present different types of antigens, resulting in different responses.

this was helpful: https://www.ebi.ac.uk/interpro/potm/2005_2/Page2.htm

name: monocyte
explanation: A type of white blood cell which originates in the bone marrow, and upon arriving at the site where they are needed, can differentiate into macrophages and dendritic cells.

name: mucous membrane
explanation: Membrane that lines various cavities in the body and surrounds internal organs. Consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells that cover a layer of loose connective tissue. You can find this on multiple body openings such as the eyes, ears, nose, and mouth.

name: multiple sclerosis
explanation: A disease of the nervous system in which the insulating covers of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord are damaged.This damage disrupts the ability of parts of the nervous system to communicate, resulting in a range of signs and symptoms, including physical, mental, and sometimes psychiatric problems.

name: natural killer cell

vettings.explanation: Natural killer cells are lymphocytes, they patrol the body and are able to bind to certain tumour cells and virus infected cells.
vettings.author: jacob

explanation: Upon release in close proximity to a cell slated for killing, perforin (or another chemical) forms pores in the cell membrane of the target cell, creating an aqueous channel through which the granzymes and associated molecules can enter, inducing either apoptosis or osmotic cell lysis.

name: neutrophil
explanation: Neutrophils are the most abundant type of granulocytes and the most abundant type of white blood cells in mammals.  They form an essential part of the innate immune system.  They are formed from stem cells in the bone marrow, are short-lived, and highly mobile (as they can enter parts of tissue where other cells/molecules wouldn't be able to enter otherwise).

name: passive immunity
explanation: Passive immunity is a type of immunity which is a result of introducing antibodies from another organism. This is sometimes short-term which is why injections to boost immune defense against specific viruses may need to be repeated at set points, ie. every ten years.

name: perforin
explanation: a protein, released by natural killer cells of the immune system, that destroys targeted cells by punching holes in the membrane

name: phagocytic cell

vettings.explanation: Within the immune system, a phagocytic cell uses phagocytosis (i.e. it engulfs a solid particle to form an internal compartment known as a phagosome) to remove pathogens and cell debris.  For example, when a macrophage ingests a pathogenic microorganism, the pathogen becomes trapped in a phagosome which then fuses with a lysosome to form a phagolysosome where enzymes and toxic peroxides digest the pathogen.  Bacteria, dead tissue cells, and small mineral particles are all examples of objects that may be phagocytized.
vettings.author: daniel

explanation: Phagocytes are cells that protect the body by ingesting (phagocytosing) harmful foreign particles, bacteria, and dead or dying cells.

name: phagocytosis
explanation: Phagocytosis is a process used by cells where the cell binds to an item such as a virus or infected cell, and engulfs it.

name: plasma cell
explanation: A plasma cell is derived from a B cell and produces a specific antibody.

name: pyrogen
explanation: A pyrogen is a substance (usually generated by bacteria) that produces a fever when released into the blood.

name: SCID
explanation:
Severe Combined Immunodeficiency - a group of monogenic immunodeficiencies that results in a inhibits the development of t lymphocytes (and sometimes B lymphocytes and NK lymphocytes). Infants suffering from SCID will therefore have drastically weakened immune systems. 

Some examples of SCID are ADA-SCID (lack gene encoding for ADA enzyme) and X-linked SCID (mutation on X chromosome).

name: secondary immune response
explanation: The second time an immune system is exposed to a certain antigen, it can react more efficiently and quicker because immunological memory exists for it and the body can immediately start producing antibodies.

name: secreted antibody
explanation: Secreted by B cells of the adaptive immune system, can come in a soluble form carried by blood plasma or a membrane-bound form attached to the surface of a B  cell called a B cell receptor.

name: septic shock
explanation: A serious medical condition that occurs when sepsis, which is organ injury or damage in response to infection, leads to dangerously low blood pressure and abnormalities in cellular metabolism.

name: skin
explanation: The soft, protective outer covering of our body. It is part of our innate immune system, by simply keeping most of the custy things in life away from us.

name: specific defense mechanism
explanation:
A specific defense mechanism consists of mechanisms and agents that target specific antigens.  It accomplishes five tasks: 
1.) Recognition - the antigen or cell is recognized as self or non-self
2.) Lymphocyte selection - the immune system selects from among billions of lymphocytes, each equipped to target a different antigen
3.) Lymphocyte activation - the binding of the antigen to a lymphocyte activates the lymphocyte and initiates proliferation
4.) Destruction of the foreign substance - lymphocytes and antibodies destroy or immobilize the foreign substance
5.) Memorization - long-lived "memory" lymphocytes are produced and can quickly recognize and respond to future exposures to the antigen or foreign cell.

name: T cell
explanation: A T cell, (AKA T lymphocyte) is a type of white blood cell which is an important part of the immune system. They are one of the two most important types of lymphocytes, the other being B lymphocytes, in terms of the specific immune response to antigens in the body.

name: T cell receptor
explanation: molecule found on the surface of T lymphoytes which is responsible for binding to antigens.

name: vaccination
explanation: Vaccination is the administration of antigenic material to stimulate an individual's immune system to develop adaptive immunity to a pathogen. Vaccines can prevent or ameliorate morbidity from infection.

name: ADH
explanation: A hormone that regulates and balances the amount of water in your blood. It is made by the hypothalamus and stored in the pituitary gland, and tells kidneys how much water to conserve.

name: afferent arteriole
explanation: The afferent arterioles are a group of blood vessels that branch from the renal artery that supply the kidney. They play an important role in the regulation of blood pressure.

name: ammonia
explanation: Ammonia (for the most part) is formed in the body when protein is broken down by bacteria in the intestines. The liver converts it into urea, and it is then eliminated in urine.

name: angiotensinogen
explanation: RAAS (system that regulates blood volume and pressure) requires angiotensinogen. It is a serum from the liver and is the precursor for all other angiotensin molecules. With the addition of renin blood pressure and volume will reduce.

name: ascending limb
explanation: A segment of the loop of Henle, draining urine into the distal convoluted tubule. As filtrate ascends the thin segment of the ascending limb, NaCl diffuses out of the permeable tubule into the interstitial fluid, increasing the osmolarity of the medulla. The thick segment continues the active transport of salt from the filtrate into the interstitial fluid, and filtrate becomes progressively more dilute as it moves up to the cortex.

name: blood
explanation:
Blood is the red fluid that circulates in our blood vessels.
The main function of blood is to act as the body's transport system.
It also has a major role in the body's defense against infection.
A type of connective tissue.

name: Bowman's capsule
explanation: A capsule-shaped membranous structure surrounding the glomerulus of each nephron in the kidneys of mammals that extracts wastes, excess salts, and water from the blood.

name: cortical nephron
explanation: A cortical nephron is a type of nephron differentiated by the location of its loop of Henle. In cortical nephrons, it is located near where the renal medulla meets the renal cortex.

name: countercurrent exchange
explanation: Exchange of materials by currents travelling in opposite directions

name: distal tubule
explanation: The distal tubule is part of the kidney nephron between the Loop of Henle and the collecting duct system. It regulates the amount of K+ secreted into the filtrate, the amount of NaCl reabsorbed, and pH.

name: efferent arteriole
explanation: Efferent arterioles carries blood away from the glomerulus.

name: excretory organ
explanation: Excretory organs are the organs that make up the excretory system, for example the kidneys, large intestine, liver, skin, and lungs.

name: filtrate
explanation: A fluid (containing water, salt, bicarbonate, urea, glucose and other solutes - never proteins or blood cells) that filters through the glomerulus (removing water and salt)

name: glomerulus
explanation: A network of capillaries located at the beginning of a nephron in the kidney. It serves as the first stage of the filtering process of blood in its formation of urine. It is also surrounded by a sac known as the Bowman's Capsule, which together constitute a renal corpuscle, the basic filtration unit of the kidney.

name: hyperosmotic
explanation:
Increased osmotic pressure.
Having an osmolality greater than another fluid.

name: hypoosmotic
explanation: A solution with a lesser concentration of solute ( fresh water compared to salt water).

name: JGA
explanation: Juxtaglomerular apparatus is a structure within the kidney which regulates the functions of each nephron. It is located next to the glomerulus, and this is where it derives its name.

name: juxtamedullary nephron
explanation: Nephrons residing in the cortex, only goes near medulla in birds and mammals

name: loop of Henle
explanation: A hairpin turn with a descending and ascending limb, located between the proximal and distal tubules of the kidney. In the descending limb, water continues to be reabsorbed, moving out of the tubule by osmosis because of the increase in solute concentration along the medulla. In the ascending limb, the membrane is impermeable to water. NaCl diffuses into the interstitial fluid, causing the filtrate to become more dilute as it moves up to the cortex.

name: lumen
explanation: Lumen is the space inside a tubular structure such as an artery. The lumen of an artery is were the blood flows.

name: metabolic waste disposal
explanation: Metabolic wastes are substances left over from metabolic processes that the organism can't use. They are excreted in a form of water solutes through the excretory organs (except CO2 which is excreted with water vapor throug hthe lungs).

name: nephron
explanation:
the basic structure of the kidney, filtering blood to control water (and other soluble substances like salt) by reabsorbing vital nutrients and excreting the rest as urine.

this is a helpful: https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~rwest/link-suggestion/wpcd_2008-09_augmented/wp/n/Nephron.htm

name: osmoconformer
explanation: Organisms (marine) that maintain an internal osmotic pressure that is equal to the pressure of their outer environment. This minimizes the osmotic gradient which means less energy is expended to regulate these gradients. A disadvantage is that the organism is subject to changes of the osmolarity of their environment,

name: osmolarity
explanation:
Measure of solute concentration
Defined as the number of osmoles (Osm) of solute per litre (L) of solution with the units being Osm/L.

name: osmoregulation
explanation: The maintenance of constant osmotic pressure in the fluids of an organism by the control of water and salt concentrations.

name: outer medulla
explanation: The outer medulla is a part of the medulla full of tubules similar to those in the renal cortex. It may also contain capillaries and thin segments of the renal loop.

name: peritubular capillaries
explanation: tiny blood vessels that travel alongside nephrons allowing reabsorption and secretion between blood and the inner lumen of the nephron

name: protonephridia
explanation: An excretory system with a network of dead-end tubules lacking internal openings. Each protonephridium is capped with a flame bulb, which has a tuft of cilia that beats during filtration to draw water and solutes from the interstitial fluid through the bulb, releasing filtrate into the tubule network, then out into the external environment as urine.

name: proximal tubule
explanation: The proximal tubule is a portion of the duct system that Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle in the cortex. One of the most important functions of the proximal tubule is the reabsorption of most of the NaCl and water from the initial filtrate volume.

name: reabsorption
explanation: The process by which the nephron removes water and solutes from the tubular fluid and returns them to the blood.

name: renal medulla
explanation: The nephron can be divided into two areas: the cortex (outer area) and renal medulla (inner area). The renal medulla contains many sections, known as the medulla pyramid, which each contain thousands of nephrons. The loop of Henle also dives into the renal medulla, extracting water from the filtrate.

name: secretion
explanation: A process by which substances are produced and discharged from a cell, gland, or organ for a particular function in the organism or for excretion.

name: selectively-permeable membrane
explanation: It is a membrane which allows certain types of ions or molecules to pass through it by means of active and passive transport.

name: transport epithelium
explanation: A substance crosses the epithelium by being transported by membrane transporters across the cells membrane.

name: urea
explanation: waste product f mammals, soluble in water non toxic energy expensive

name: urethra
explanation: A tube through which urine is expelled from the bladder to the outside.

name: uric acid
explanation: Uric acid is the main nitrogenous waste excreted by snails, birds, insects, and most reptiles. It is not toxic and is largely insoluble in water.

name: urine
explanation: The fluid stored in the bladder and discharged through the urethra. It allows the body to eliminate excess water and salt and contains nitrogen compounds like urea and other waste that is removed from the blood by the kidneys.

name: alpha cells
explanation: An endocrine cell in the Islet of Langerhans of the pancreas that produce glucagon, which will help increase blood sugar levels.

name: blood calcium level
explanation:
Calcium is the most common mineral in the body and one of the most important. The body needs it to build and fix bones and teeth, help nerves work, make muscles squeeze together, help blood clot, and help the heart to work. Almost all of the calcium in the body is stored in bone, and is taken into the body by food or liquids. 

If there is a falling level of Ca2+ in the blood, PTH is released, and will stimulate the release of Ca2+ from the bones, and an increased uptake of Ca2+ in the kidneys. This eventually leads to blood calcium levels rising to their normal levels.

name: calcitrol
explanation: It is an active metabolite of vitamin D, and it increases the level of calcium in the blood. It does this by increasing re absorption of calcium by the kidneys.

name: control pathway
explanation: The secretion of hormones is regulated by control pathways, including negative feedback loops, positive feedback or antagonistic pairs. Feedback loops connect the response to the initial stimulus. In negative feedback loops, an essential part of many hormone pathways, especially those involved in homeostasis, the response reduces the initial stimulus.

name: cortisol
explanation: Cortisol is a hormone made in the cortex of adrenal glands and released into blood to transport around the body. It is released in response to stress and high blood glucose levels. Effects of cortisol include reduction in blood sugar levels,   and acting as an anti-inflammatory.

name: diabetes mellitus
explanation: Diabetes is a metabolic disease in which someone has high blood sugar levels. It consists of type I and type II - type I is due to the pancreas's inability to produce insulin, and usually occurs in younger patients. Someone with type II diabetes has decreased reception to insulin, and can be linked to obesity. Symptoms of both types include frequent urination, increased thirst, and increased hunger

name: ecdysteroid

vettings.explanation: They are the androgens of insects (steroids that are precursors of estrogens), but may also be present in plants as protection agents against insects (these are called phytoecdysteroids)
vettings.author: nuala

explanation: insect moulting and sex hormones

name: endocrine gland
explanation: These glands release hormones directly into the blood (rather than through a duct), forming the endocrine system of the body. Examples include the hypothalamus, the pituitary gland, the parathyroid, thyroid, pancreas, testes, ovaries... see the picture below for the others.

name: glucagon
explanation: Glucagon is a peptide hormone released by the alpha cells of the pancreas to stimulate the liver into breaking down more glycogen into glucose, causing blood glucose levels to rise and reach their normal levels.

name: hormone cascade pathway

vettings.explanation: Signals to the brain stimulate the hypothalamus to secrete a hormone that either stimulates or inhibits release of an anterior pituitary hormone. This hormone travels through the bloodstream then acts on an endocrine gland, stimulating release of another hormone that induces a response in target cells.
vettings.author: serena

explanation: A pathway formed by the interactions between the hypothalamus, anterior pituitary and the target endocrine gland.

name: hydrophobic (lipid soluble) hormone
explanation: Hormones are divided into three groups - polypeptides, amines and steroids. Steroid hormones and other non-polar hormones are lipid-soluble which allow them to easily pass through cell membranes. They diffuse across membranes of endocrine cells, entering the bloodstream where the hormone binds to a transport protein. It then enters the target cell, binding to a signal receptor either in the cytoplasm or in the nucleus. The response is usually a change in gene expression.

name: insulin
explanation: Insulin is secreted in response to high blood glucose levels. It is produced by beta cells in the pancreas. The main function of insulin is to promote the storage of glucose from the blood as glycogen.

name: intercellular communication
explanation: There are three stages of intercellular communication: reception, transduction, and response. In reception, a target cell detects a signal from a molecule binding to a receptor protein. Transduction refers to the changes that occur when binding occurs (for example the activation of proteins via removal of phosphate groups). Finally, this transduced signal results in a cellular response - which could be any cellular activity in the body.

name: intracellular receptor

vettings.explanation: will also receive and respond to signals, like neurotransmitters or hormones
vettings.author: hannah

explanation: Receptors located inside the cell rather than on its cell membrane.

name: local regulator
explanation: Involved in paracrine (cell-cell) signalling. A cell releases a a local regulator that will diffuse through the surrounding fluid (extracellular fluid) to a nearby cell.

name: neurosecretory cell
explanation: It is a type of neuron whose primary role is to translate neural signals into chemical stimuli. Such cells produce secretions called neurohormones that travel along the neuron axon and are typically released into the bloodstream at neurohemal organs, regions in which the axon endings are in close contact with blood capillaries.

name: pancreatic islet

vettings.explanation: also contain alpha cells which produce glucagon
vettings.author: hannah

explanation: Also known as an Islets of Langerhans, they are small bundles of cells in the pancreas. Contain many cells including beta cells which produce the hormone insulin.

name: polypeptide hormone
explanation: Hormones are often divided into three groups- polypeptides, amines and steroids. Polypeptide hormones (proteins and peptides) like insulin, are water-soluble, meaning they are released by exocytosis from the endocrine cell, enter the bloodstream, before binding to a receptor on the surface of the target cell. This leads to a change in cytoplasmic function or gene transcription.

name: positive feedback
explanation:
The increase in 

For example,

name: prostaglandin
explanation: Prostaglandins are found in almost every human and  animal tissue, and are derived from fatty acids. They are different from endocrine hormones in that they can be made anywhere in the body, not just at a specific site. They stimulate reactions in tissues by binding to different receptors (the kind of reaction depends on what kind of receptor it is).

name: PTH

vettings.explanation: The parathyroid hormone is secreted by the parathyroid glands. It is used to main homeostasis with blood calcium levels.
vettings.author: sharon

vettings.explanation: To add on to sharon, PTH will increase blood calcium levels when they are too low. It will do this by stimulating bones to release calcium and the kidneys to uptake calcium (so the kidneys can add calcium into blood). PTH also stimulates production of active vitamin d in the kindeys, which will signal for the intestines to release calcium into the blood.
vettings.author: hannah

explanation: Parathyroid hormone

name: receptor
explanation: a protein on the membranes of a cell that receives a signal from outside of the cell. In the context of hormone regulation, protein receptors on a target cell will receive a hormonal signal that will then stimulate change in the cell.

name: somatostatin
explanation: It is a growth-inhibiting, peptide hormone that affects the body by hindering the secretion of various other hormones.   It stops the unnatural rapid reproduction of cells  such as those that may occur in tumors. The hormone also acts as a neurotransmitter and has a role in the gastrointestinal tract.

name: target cell

vettings.explanation: A target cell is selectively activated by a specific agent (e.g. a hormone).
vettings.author: nuala

explanation: A target cell is the cell which bears receptors for a hormone, so it is the end point for a hormone.

name: type 1 diabetes
explanation: Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune disorder in which the immune system destroys beta cells of the pancreas, affecting its ability to produce insulin. Insulin takes up glucose from blood, decreasing the blood glucose concentration.

name: ACTH
explanation: Adrenocorticotropic hormone, or ACTH, is a hormone that is produced and secreted by the anterior pituitary gland. It is a key part of the HPA - axis, and is produced in response to stress. It's main effects include the production and release of cortisol by the adrenal cortex.

name: adrenal cortex

vettings.explanation: The adrenal cortex responds to endocrine signals. Stressful stimuli causes the hypothalamus to secrete a hormone stimulating the anterior pituitary gland to release ACTH. When ACTH reaches the adrenal cortex, it stimulates endocrine cells to synthesize and secrete corticosteroids.
vettings.author: serena

explanation: Mediates the stress response through the production of mineralocorticoids and glucocorticoids.

name: Bartholin's gland
explanation: Two pea-sized compound racemose glands located slightly behind and to the right and left of the opening of the vagina and secrete mucus to lubricate the vagina.

name: bulbourethral gland
explanation: The bulbourethral gland is also known as the Cowper's gland is one of the two small exocrine glands located beneath the prostate gland at the beginning of the internal portion of the penis; they add fluids to semen during the process of ejaculation.

name: epididymis
explanation: A coiled tube adjacent to the testis where sperm are stored. Sperm pass through these tubules completing maturation and becoming motile.

name: follicle
explanation: A follicle (in general) is a small secretory gland that resembles a cavity or sac. An ovarian follicle is a spheroid group of cells found in the ovaries. They are induced by follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) to express luteinizing hormone (LH).

name: follicular phase
explanation: The phase of the estrous cycle during which follicles in the ovary mature, ending in ovulation.

name: GnRH

vettings.explanation: GnRH is secreted by the hypothalamus, which directs the anterior pituitary glands to secrete FSH and LH which regulate spermatogenesis.
vettings.author: serena

explanation: Releasing hormone responsible for the release of LH and FSH

name: gonad
explanation: A gonad is also known as the sex gland or the reproductive gland, is an endocrine gland that produces the gametes (sex cells) of an organism. In the female of the species the reproductive cells are the egg cells, and in the male the reproductive cells are the sperm.

name: labia minora
explanation: Pair of slender skin folds that surround the openings of the vagina and urethra.

name: luteal phase
explanation: The luteal phase is the stage of the menstrual cycle that occurs after ovulation, and before menstruation starts. During this phase, the lining of the uterus becomes thicker to prepare for the possibility of pregnancy.

name: mammary gland
explanation: The milk-producing gland of women.

name: menstrual cycle
explanation: A regular natural change that occurs in the female reproductive system of humans and a few other mammals. Result of the egg not being fertilized by the sperm.

name: menstrual flow
explanation: Menstruation occurs when the lining of the walls of your uterus are no longer needed for the month cause ya didn't get pregnant (yay that's good). It flows from your uterus to your cervix, then out your vagina.

name: oviduct
explanation: The oviduct, or fallopian tube, is a tube that goes from the ovary to the uterus. During ovulation, the egg is released into the abdominal cavity near the opening of the oviduct. Cilia on the epithelial lining collect the egg by drawing fluid from the body cavity into the oviduct, then using contractions to bring the egg down the duct to the uterus.

name: oxytocin
explanation: Oxytocin is a hormone that is produced by the hypothalamus and released by the posterior pituitary. It is released into the bloodstream during childbirth as a response to the stretching of the cervix and the uterus. Leydig cells in some species have been shown to have the means to produce testicular oxycotin in males.

name: penis
explanation: The primary sexual organ that males use to inseminate sexually receptive mates during copulation

name: posterior pituitary hormone
explanation: Stores two hormones secreted by the hypothalamus gland for later release (oxycotin and ADH)

name: primary sex characteristics
explanation: Primary sex characteristics refer to changes to the sexual organs themselves (uterus, vagina, penis, and testes). Secondary sex characteristics refer to other visible changes that mark adult maturation such as changes in height and body shape.

name: secondary sex characteristics
explanation: Secondary sex characteristics are features that appear during puberty but do not have a direct reproductive function. For example, growth of body hair, development of breasts, or deepening of the voice.

name: seminal vesicle
explanation: Also known as seminal glands, the seminal vesicles are located within the pelvis that secrete fluid that in part makes up the semen.

name: seminiferous tubules
explanation: Tubules located within the testes where meiosis occurs along with the subsequent creation of male gametes, spermatozoa.

name: thyroid
explanation:
The thyroid gland is an endocrine gland located in your neck, which produces triiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4) which are created from iodine and tyrosine. The thyroid also produces the hormone calcitonin, which plays a role in calcium homeostasis.

Hormonal output from the thyroid is regulated by thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) secreted from the anterior pituitary gland, which itself is regulated by thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH) produced by the hypothalamus.

name: vas deferens
explanation: The tube in the male reproductive system through which sperm travel from the epididymis to the urethra. Each goes around and behind the bladder, where it joins a duct from the seminal vesicle, forming a short ejaculatory duct.

name: adrenal capsule
explanation: The adrenal capsule is the fatty tissue that surrounds the adrenal glands, which are located above the kidneys on both sides of the body.

name: adrenal gland

vettings.explanation: They are located above the kidneys on either part of the body, and consist of the medulla and the cortex.
vettings.author: nuala

explanation: An endocrine gland that produce a variety of hormones including adrenaline and the steroids aldosterone and cortisol.

name: corticosteroid

vettings.explanation: It is part of the body's long term stress response, and can be classified as either glucocorticoids (help break down fats, carbohydrates, and proteins), or mineralocorticoids (regulate the balance of salt in the body).
vettings.author: nuala

explanation: A type of steroid that is produced in the adrenal cortex

name: glucocorticoid
explanation: Glucocorticoids are a type of steroid hormones. GCs are part of the feedback mechanism in the immune system which reduces certain aspects of immune function, such as reduction of inflammation.
